| 17  | [Ware Creek School](/Ware_Creek_School) | Ware Creek School | December 6, 1996<br>(#96001443) | Eastern side of NC 1103, 0.3 miles southeast of its junction with NC 1112<br>• 35°25′12″N 76°56′19″W&#xfeff; / &#xfeff;35.42°N 76.938611°W&#xfeff; / 35.42; -76.938611&#xfeff; ([Ware Creek School)](/Ware_Creek_School))<br>[Blounts Creek](/Blounts_Creek,_North_Carolina) | The [Ware Creek School](/Ware_Creek_School), located on the eastern side of NC 1103 near its junction with NC 1112 in the vicinity of [Blounts Creek](/Blounts_Creek,_North_Carolina), is a significant example of early 20th-century rural educational architecture. Constructed around 1910, this one-room or two-room schoolhouse would have served the local agricultural community, playing a crucial role in providing basic education before the widespread consolidation of schools. The building's design would have been simple and functional, typically of wood-frame construction, reflecting the limited resources and practical needs of rural education. Its listing in 1996 recognizes its architectural integrity as a surviving example of a type of building that was once ubiquitous but is now increasingly rare, and its historical importance in documenting the evolution of public education in [Beaufort County](/Beaufort_County,_North_Carolina). A place where chalk dust and youthful dreams once mingled. |
| 18  | [Washington Historic District](/Washington_Historic_District_(Washington,_North_Carolina)) | Washington Historic District | February 9, 1979<br>(#79001661) | Roughly bounded by Jacks Creek, the [Pamlico River](/Pamlico_River), and Hackney, 3rd, Market, 5th, Harvey, and 2nd Sts.<br>• 35°32′37″N 77°03′17″W&#xfeff; / &#xfeff;35.543611°N 77.054722°W&#xfeff; / 35.543611; -77.054722&#xfeff; ([Washington Historic District)](/Washington_Historic_District_(Washington,_North_Carolina)))<br>[Washington](/Washington,_NC) | The sprawling [Washington Historic District](/Washington_Historic_District_(Washington,_North_Carolina)), added to the [National Register](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places) in 1979, encompasses a substantial portion of the city of [Washington](/Washington,_NC), often referred to as "The Original Washington." Roughly defined by Jacks Creek, the [Pamlico River](/Pamlico_River), and a network of streets including Hackney, 3rd, Market, 5th, Harvey, and 2nd, this district is a rich tapestry of architectural styles and historical periods. It features an impressive array of residential, commercial, and institutional buildings, dating from the late 18th century through the early 20th century. Architectural styles range from [Federal](/Federal_architecture) and [Georgian](/Georgian_architecture) to [Victorian](/Victorian_architecture) (including [Queen Anne](/Queen_Anne_style_architecture_in_the_United_States) and [Italianate](/Italianate_architecture)) and [Neoclassical Revival](/Neoclassical_architecture). The district's significance lies in its ability to tell the comprehensive story of Washington's development as a vital port city and regional center, showcasing its economic prosperity and changing urban landscape over nearly two centuries. It's a living archive, where every street corner has a tale, if you care to listen. |
| 19  | [Zion Episcopal Church](/Zion_Episcopal_Church_(Washington,_North_Carolina)) | Zion Episcopal Church | August 16, 2000<br>(#00000988) | [U.S. Route 264](/U.S._Route_264), 0.2 miles east of its junction with NC 1601<br>• 35°31′23″N 76°56′05″W&#xfeff; / &#xfeff;35.523056°N 76.934722°W&#xfeff; / 35.523056; -76.934722&#xfeff; ([Zion Episcopal Church)](/Zion_Episcopal_Church_(Washington,_North_Carolina)))<br>[Washington](/Washington,_NC) | The [Zion Episcopal Church](/Zion_Episcopal_Church_(Washington,_North_Carolina)), located off [U.S. Route 264](/U.S._Route_264) east of its junction with NC 1601 near [Washington](/Washington,_NC), is a significant religious edifice with a history stretching back to the mid-19th century. Built in 1842, this church is a notable example of [Gothic Revival architecture](/Gothic_Revival_architecture), a style frequently employed for ecclesiastical buildings to evoke medieval grandeur and spiritual reverence. Its design typically includes pointed arch windows, steeply pitched roofs, and often intricate wooden detailing, reflecting the period's romanticized view of Gothic cathedrals. The church's listing in 2000 highlights its architectural distinctiveness and its enduring role as a spiritual and community anchor for over a century and a half in [Beaufort County](/Beaufort_County,_North_Carolina). A place where faith, and perhaps a touch of architectural ambition, converged. |

